# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sailing-ship-tactics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The **Third Portuguese India Armada** was assembled in 1501 upon the order of King Manuel I of Portugal and placed under the command of João da Nova.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It was small compared to other armadas of the same type and was formed for commercial purposes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nonetheless, it engaged in the first significant Portuguese naval battle in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada discovered the uninhabited islands of Ascension and Saint Helena in the South Atlantic Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some speculate that it was the first Portuguese armada to reach Ceylon (now Sri Lanka).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Little is known about the Third Armada of 1501 as opposed to other early Portuguese India armadas.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Chroniclers' accounts are scant on details and differ significantly at several points.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Very few contemporary documents offer substantive information, such as reconciliations of differing accounts or missing details.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada was primarily a commercial run to India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It is confirmed to have been composed of four ships: two owned by the crown and two privately owned.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] There may have been a fifth supply ship.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This list of captains is given in João de Barros's *Décadas*, Damião de Góis's *Chronica*, Fernão Lopes de Castanheda's *História*, Diogo do Couto's list, Manuel de Faria e Sousa's *Asia* and Quintella's *Annaes*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Fernão Pacheco replaces Barbosa in several lists: Gaspar Correia's *Lendas* and the *Relação das Naus*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The *Livro de Lisuarte de Abreu* replaces Novais and Barbosa with Rui de Abreu and Duarte Pacheco, respectively.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The modest armada carried 350–400 men, only 80 of which were armed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Its admiral was João da Nova, a Galician-born minor noble.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He was *Alcalde Pequeno* (municipal magistrate) of Lisbon, and his principal recommendation to the admiralship was probably his connection to the powerful Portuguese nobleman Tristão da Cunha.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The owners of the two private ships, D. Álvaro of Braganza and Bartolomeo Marchionni, a Florentine, had jointly outfitted the *Anunciada*, one of the ships of the Second India Armada of Pedro Álvares Cabral that was still at sea at the time.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It was a considerable gamble for them to outfit the new ships before knowing the results of the previous enterprise.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The *Anunciada* safely returned to Lisbon later in 1501 with a large cargo of spices.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It has also been suggested that da Nova was charged to block any attempt by the Spanish to enter the spice trade.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] If true, given the small size of his fleet, he was entrusted with a very delicate mission.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] One of the passengers on the fleet was Paio Rodrigues, employed by D. Álvaro of Braganza to remain in India as a factor for the private consortium.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Another was Álvaro de Braga, a crown factor who was heading for the African port of Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The objective of the Third Armada was wholly commercial.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Its mission was to go to India, load up with spices, and return home.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The journey was expected to be uneventful.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The journey's destination was Calicut (known as *Calecute* in some sources, now Kozhikode), the principal spice hub in the state of Kerala and the dominant city-state on the Malabar coast of India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada expected – or hoped – that the well-equipped Second India Armada of Pedro Álvares Cabral, which had departed in the previous year (1500), had succeeded in its ambassadorial mission to secure a treaty with Calicut and set up a factory (*feitoria*, a trading hub) there.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada was unaware that Cabral's Second Armada had not only failed in its mission, but it also began hostilities between Portugal and Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] João da Nova's Third Armada was sailing into a war that it did not expect and for which it was not equipped.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada also seems to have had a planned intermediary destination at Sofala, where Cabral had been instructed to set up a factory.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Correia, the crown ship of Francisco de Novais was designated to trade for gold in Sofala and leave the factor Álvaro de Braga, the clerk Diogo Barbosa (same name as captain) and an additional twenty-two men.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Cabral's Second Armada had also already failed that mission: there was no Portuguese factory in Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada could not have delayed its departure until the arrival of the news of the Second Armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The seasonal monsoon wind patterns of the Indian Ocean forced India-bound expeditions to leave Lisbon by April at the latest in order to find favorable southeasterly summer winds from Africa to India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Those same wind patterns determined that returning fleets could only arrive in Europe in the summer, June at the earliest.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although the difference between one fleet's departure and another fleet's arrival was only a few months, outbound fleets could not delay their departure until the previous year's fleet returned; if they did, an entire year would be lost.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Therefore, both the crown and the private consortiums were willing to equip and launch the Third Armada in March 1501 before they received any news of the outcome of the Second Armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The first ship of the Second Armada to arrive only did so in late June.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova's Third Armada would learn of the Second Armada's voyage along its own voyage from notes and letters left by Cabral's ships at African staging posts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Even if the Third Armada learned about the misfortune of the Second Armada, the aforementioned conditions meant that it could not go home to acquire reinforcements or otherwise change the circumstances of its journey.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Lightly armed, it would have to press on, sneak into India stealthily, avoid Calicut, load spices at friendly ports, and leave, all as quickly as possible.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The date of the third Portuguese armada's departure from Lisbon to India has variously been quoted as 1 March, 5 March, 11 March, 26–27 March or 10 April.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Two chronicles claimed the ships discovered Ascension Island during the outward voyage, naming it Conception Island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Thus, João de Barros wrote that passing eight degrees beyond the equator, towards the south, an island was found to which the name Concepcão was given whilst Damião de Góis’ later chronicle described the sighting of an island south of the line which was named Conçeicam.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] There are at least three reasons why it is thought this name was quoted by de Barros in error, this later being repeated by de Góis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] First, the Church of Rome has long celebrated the feast of the Immaculate Conception of the Virgin Mary on the fixed date of 8 December, yet by then the third armada had already reached India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Second, the Portuguese Cantino Planisphere, completed in 1502 after the third armada returned, shows the newly sighted island marked as *ilha achada e chamada Ascenssam* [island found and called Ascension], not as Conception.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Third, in 1503 a division of the 4th Portuguese India Armada (Gama, 1502) under Estêvão da Gama also named the island as Ascension, not as Conception.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It is usually presumed that the island was discovered on the movable feast of Ascension Day, which fell on 20 May in 1501, 39 days after Easter.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Two sources, a letter from King Manuel I of Portugal and Gaspar Corrêa’s chronicle, made no mention of either Ascension or Conception, instead describing a visit to Brazil.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The fleet crossed the Cape of Good Hope on July 7, 1501 without a known incident.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It anchored at Mossel Bay (*Aguada de São Brás*).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] There, Nova found a note in a shoe by a watering hole.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The note was left about a month earlier by Pêro de Ataíde, one of the captains of the returning Second Armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Ataíde's note, addressed to all captains bound for India, warned that Calicut had become hostile to the Portuguese, but that Cochin (*Cochim*, now Kochi) and Cannanore (now Kannur) were still friendly ports where spices could be procured.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It also recommended India-bound captains to go to Malindi, where Pedro Álvares Cabral left letters that contained more detailed information.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Centuries later, the South African government declared the milkwood tree where Ataíde hung his shoe a national monument and erected a shoe-shaped postbox below it.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] A letter written by Pedro Quaresma to King Manuel II described a visit to this location a few years later in 1506.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This same reference source includes a description of the walls of a ruined *hermida* dedicated to St Blaise on the high ground (Cape St Blaise) between two coves at Mossel Bay in 1576.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Later in his outward voyage, Da Nova is also said to have discovered what has since been called Juan de Nova Island in the Mozambique Channel.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In the middle of July 1501, the Third Armada arrived at Mozambique Island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Disregarding instructions, Nova decided against dispatching Novais's ship to Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova probably concluded that he needed to take all of his men due to the threat of a military engagement in India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Soon after, he set sail up the East African coast.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] At the same time, Nova possibly discovered Juan de Nova Island in the Mozambique Channel and the Farquhar atoll, part of the Seychelles, which were named the "João da Nova islands" until the 19th century.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Around the same time, the armada arrived at the Swahili citadel of Kilwa (*Quiloa*).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] A Portuguese *degredado* (convict exile), António Fernandes, greeted them on the beach or on a rowboat.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Barros and Góis, he was António Fernandes, who carried letters from Cabral; Correia writes that he was Pêro Esteves, who was carrying no letters.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The *degredado* informed Nova of the state of affairs in Kilwa.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Barros suggests that, on this occasion, João da Nova personally met Muhammad Arcone, a Kilwan noble who would later play a critical role in Portuguese–Kilwan affairs.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia notes that Nova was wary of approaching Kilwa, and refused to go ashore despite repeated invitations; he had the degredado negotiate the provision of some supplies, probably citrus fruit, from the city for his scurvy-sick crews and hurriedly moved on.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Barros suggests that in late July, the Third Armada immediately set sail for India after it left Kilwa.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia claims that Nova sailed first to Malindi to deliver a letter from King Manuel I of Portugal to the Sultan of Malindi.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Correia, the sultan received the Portuguese well, supplying them amply with biscuits, rice, butter, chickens, sheep and other foods.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He further writes that it was now that Nova received the letters that Cabral had dispatched by a messenger from Mozambique, from which he learned more about the Zamorin (monarch) of Calicut, the Portuguese factory at Cochin and the friendly relations with Cannanore and Quilon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In this version, the Third Armada left Malindi on July 28, 1501, and crossed the Indian Ocean after 18 days.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In August 1501, João da Nova's Third Armada arrived in India at the Santa Maria islands off the Malabar coast.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Correia, Nova named the islands because of the feast of the Assumption of Mary (August 15).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Narratives about the ensuing events differ.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Both narratives agree that the Third Armada eventually began going down the Indian coast to Kerala, attempting to capture two merchant ships, allegedly from Calicut, near Mount d'Eli (now Ezhimala Hill) along the way.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The two-month delay between the Third Armada's reputed arrival in India (August) and its first recorded activities in India (November) has been subject to speculation.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia suggests that the Third Armada simply lingered in the area between Batecala and Mount d'Eli to trade and perhaps engage in piracy before it headed south to Cannanore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Others hypothesize that during this interlude, Nova launched exploratory ventures far to the south below Cape Comorin to locate the fabled island of Taprobana (Ceylon), the world's main source of cinnamon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada arrived in Cannanore in November.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] They were well received by the Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore, who immediately urged João da Nova to load his ships with spices from the city's markets.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova rejected the offer because he first had to collect the supplies already acquired by the Portuguese factory in Cochin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Before leaving, Nova left a few agents with instructions to purchase spices, principally ginger and cinnamon, in Cannanore to be loaded later.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some sources note that Nova established the Portuguese factory in Cannanore at this point.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, the factor whom he left behind was Paio Rodrigues, a private agent of D. Álvaro of Braganza and the Marchionni consortium, not an employee of the Casa da India, the crown trading house.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Casa itself, a proxy of the Portuguese Crown, would only install a factor in Cannanore with the Fourth Armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] While he was in Cannanore, João da Nova received an embassy from the Zamorin of Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Accompanying the embassy was Gonçalo Peixoto, a Portuguese survivor of the previous year's massacre who had remained in Calicut for the past year.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In a letter to Nova, the Zamorin expressed sadness at the Calicut Massacre of December 1500, blaming it on hatred between Muslims and Christians that he never understood.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He claimed that he, as a Hindu prince, only had a desire for friendship and peace with Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Zamorin also reported that the ringleaders of the riot had been rounded up and punished, and invited Nova to Calicut to collect the wares left behind in the Portuguese factory and receive compensation.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Proposing to dispatch two ambassadors with Nova's fleet back to Lisbon, he expressed a desire to make a final treaty with King Manuel I of Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore recommended Nova to accept the offer.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Gonçalo Peixoto warned Nova to reject the offer, claiming that the Zamorin was luring him into a trap and at the time preparing a war fleet in Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova did not reply to the Zamorin's entreaty.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia asserts that Peixoto did not come; Nova agreed to the offer from the Zamorin's emissary to Cannanore and sailed to Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada anchored by the harbor there, waiting for the promised wares to be shipped from shore, when an unnamed Christian came aboard and warns him about the Zamorin's intentions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Before Nova left, he captured three merchant ships, including one owned by the Zamorin himself, at the mouth of Calicut harbor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He seized their cargoes and burned the vessels in plain view of the city.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Valuable loot from the ships included silver Indian nautical instruments, and navigational charts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Arriving in Cochin, João da Nova encountered a factor left by Cabral, Gonçalo Gil Barbosa, who reports trading difficulties in the local markets.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Indian spice merchants required payment in silver, but Cabral had left the factor only with Portuguese goods, mainly cloth.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He was expected to use the trading revenue from the sale of the Portuguese goods to buy spices.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, the Portuguese wares had little value in Indian markets, so Barbosa still had his unsold stock and was unable to obtain silver to buy spices.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The factor suspected that Arab merchant guilds had engineered a boycott of Portuguese goods in India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He also reported that the Trimumpara Raja of Cochin, despite his alliance and protection of the factory, was furious at the Portuguese because Cabral's Second Armada had departed too suddenly, not taking two noble Cochinese noble hostages with it.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Sources ascribe the lack of silver cash as the pressing problem that Nova did not anticipate.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He did not bring much because he expected to raise cash through selling Portuguese goods.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova immediately set sail back to Cannanore to see if the agents whom he left there had raised cash, but they faced the same problem.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore finally intervened, placing himself as security for the sale of spices to the Portuguese on credit and allowing the Portuguese to obtain spices.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In 1898, excavations underneath the Breakwater Office in Colombo, Sri Lanka, revealed a boulder with a Portuguese inscription, a coat of arms, and the clearly denoted date 1501.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] That was four years before Lourenço de Almeida's arrival on the island, the formal date (1505) of the Portuguese discovery of Ceylon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Much speculation has surrounded the inscription.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The earliest theory was that the boulder was an uncompleted gravestone for a Portuguese captain born in 1501 (death date missing).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, the arms and style of the inscription appeared to be of a *padrão*, the typical marker of a Portuguese claim.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some argue that the date is simply a mistake or that the "1" in 1501 is a poorly carved digit.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Another theory is that what appears to be a number is actually an acronym, ISOI (*Iesus Salvator Orientalium Indicorum* – "Jesus the Savior of the East Indies").
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nonetheless, some historians, notably Bouchon in 1980, have argued that the inscription was made by a captain of the Third Armada of 1501.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The sources that describe the journey of the armada do not record that it stumbled upon Ceylon, but the journey of the armada was poorly recorded as a whole.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Bouchon (1980) speculates that the discovery happened during an exploratory venture launched from Anjediva Island or the Santa Maria islands.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] 257) is that the journey to Ceylon was sometime in late November or early December 1501.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Under this scenario, Nova did not immediately return to Cannanore after he realized the cash problem, but rather he or one of his captains either stumbled upon Ceylon or was guided there by a local, hoping for better success there.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] None of these theories are confirmed or suggested in any written accounts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In mid-December 1501, the Third Armada was preparing to leave India, loaded with spices from Cannanore and other goods from piratical attacks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] News arrived, however, that a battle fleet led by the Zamorin was approaching.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Sometime in December, Nova's fleet was cornered by the Zamorin's fleet as he was about to leave Cannanore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Zamorin's fleet comprised nearly 40 large ships, and 180 small ships called *paraus* and *zambuks*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Raja of Cannanore urged Nova to stay under his protection and avoid conflict.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova rejected the Raja's offer, attempting to break out with a favorable breeze.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada fired its cannons to breach the Zamorin's line.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Once a breach was opened, four Portuguese ships charged into the breach in a column formation, their side cannons blasting.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The pounding from the cannons and the height of Nova's ships prevented the Calicut forces from boarding the Portuguese ships with grappling hooks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The less seaworthy fleet of the Zamorin, pursuing the escaping Portuguese, began to splinter due to intense cannon fire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The increased distance between the slowed-down Calicut fleet and the Third Armada caused the former to stop aiming to board the Portuguese ships, causing the battle to become a ranged artillery duel.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Calicut fleet retreated after it realized that its cannons' range and reloading speed could not match those of the Third Armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova gave a brief chase, finally breaking up the engagement on January 2, 1502.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] After two days of fighting, the Third Armada had sunk five large ships and about a dozen oar-driven boats.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It inflicted great damage on the remaining vessels of the Zamorin while it was not damaged much itself.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although João da Nova was not prepared for a fight, the two-day naval battle off Cannanore is regarded by some as the first significant Portuguese naval engagement in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It was not the first clash between Portuguese and Indian ships – Vasco da Gama's First Armada and Cabral's Second Armada also fought with various Indian fleets.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Earlier encounters were fought against mostly poorly armed merchant ships, pirates and isolated squads; a single well-armed caravel could win a battle against these targets with ease.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In the First Battle of Cannanore, the Zamorin of Calicut had attacked directly, deploying the best fleet he could against a small group of Portuguese merchant carracks, which were significantly less heavily armed than the ships of Gama and Cabral.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to the Portuguese Navy's official website, the battle is also historically notable for being one of the earliest recorded deliberate uses of a naval column, later called line of battle, and for being resolved by cannon fire alone.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The tactics used in the battle became increasingly prevalent as naval technology and strategy evolved, causing the battle to have been called the first modern naval battle.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In early 1502, the Third Armada captured another Calicut merchant ship near Mount d'Eli, which it sacked, burned and sunk.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It began the return voyage soon afterwards.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada made two watering stops in East Africa: first at Malindi, where Nova deposited letters that would be received later that year by Thomé Lopes, and second at Mozambique Island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] After turning around the Cape of Good Hope, Nova sailed into the South Atlantic and discovered the uninhabited island of Saint Helena while he was returning home.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It is believed that the island was named after St.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] By tradition the date is the feast day of the saint on May 21.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Jan Huyghen van Linschoten in a 2015 paper says that the date is a mistakenly quoted Protestant feast day for a discovery made two decades before the Reformation, instead suggesting May 3 as the more likely date, the feast day of the True Cross.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to legend, Nova anchored on the western side of the island and built a timber chapel at the location of the future Jamestown, Saint Helena.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The island became a routine staging post on future Portuguese expeditions to India, but its existence and location was a Portuguese secret for the next eighty years until English captain Thomas Cavendish stumbled upon it in 1588.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova's Third Armada arrived in Lisbon on September 11, 1502.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to the letters by Italian merchants in Lisbon, the Third Armada brought back 900 *cantari* (quintals) of black pepper, 550 of cinnamon, 30 of ginger, 25 of lac, and other assorted goods.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The amount of cinnamon has been cited as evidence of the theory that the armada visited Ceylon, but cinnamon was not rare in other Indian markets.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some of the cinnamon may have come from the cargoes of seized vessels.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The expedition of the Third Armada was not considered a resounding success.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although there was no significant loss of ships or men, the armada came back with fewer spices than had been anticipated; letters insinuate that the cargo holds were partially empty.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova also failed to trade for gold in Africa.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The report of the cash constraint in India and the armada's reliance on piracy to fill its holds disheartened Portuguese merchants, who had previously thought that they could make easy profits on both legs of the India run.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In contrast, the discovery of Ascension Island and Saint Helena was well received.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada arrived too late to supply information from the journey to Gama's heavily armed 4th India Armada, which had already left Lisbon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] By long tradition Saint Helena was sighted on 21 May 1502 by the four ships of the 3rd Portuguese Armada commanded by João da Nova during the return voyage to Lisbon, and that he named it Santa Helena after Saint Helena of Constantinople.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This tradition has been reviewed by a 2022 paper which concluded the Portuguese chronicles published at least 50 years later, are the sole primary source to the discovery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although contradictory in describing other events, these chronicles almost unanimously claim João da Nova found Saint Helena sometime in 1502, although none quote the precise date.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, there are several reasons for doubting da Nova made this discovery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Second, when a section of the Fourth Armada under the command of Estêvão da Gama sighted and landed at Saint Helena the following year on 30 July 1503 its scrivener Thomé Lopes regarded it as an unknown island yet named Ascension as one of five reference points to the new island’s location.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] On 12 July 1502, nearly three weeks before reaching Saint Helena, Lopes described how Estêvão da Gama’s ships met up with a section of the Fifth Armada led by Afonso de Albuquerque off the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The latter left Lisbon about six months after João da Nova’s return so Albuquerque and his captains should all have known whether João da Nova had indeed found Saint Helena.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] An anonymous Flemish traveler on one of da Gama's ships reporting that bread and victuals were running short by the time they reached the Cape, so from da Gama's perspective there was a pressing need that he be told water and meat could be found at Saint Helena.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The fact that nothing seems to have been said about the island, da Gama's scrivener Lopes regarding the island as unknown, again implies da Nova found Ascension but not Saint Helena.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The 2022 paper also reviews cartographic evidence that Saint Helena and Ascension were known to the Spanish in 1500, before either João da Nova or Estêvão da Gama sailed for India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The suggestion that João da Nova discovered Tristan da Cunha naming it Saint Helena is discounted.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] If João da Nova indeed found Saint Helena, a separate 2015 paper has reviewed another tradition that he did so on 21 May 1502.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This date appears to have first been suggested by Jan Huyghen van Linschoten in a book published in Holland in 1596.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This described how his ships left Saint Helena on 21 May 1589, this being both the feast of Saint Helena and Whitsunday.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] At first sight, this statement seems to be a contradiction - the Roman Catholic Church certainly celebrated Whitsunday that day but their feast-day of Saint Helena was on 18 August.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Linschoten's statement did not fit in with the Eastern Orthodox Church either - this faith certainly marked Saint Helena on 21 May but in 1589 celebrated Whitsun a week later, on 28 May.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The paper suggested the solution to this apparent paradox was that by the time his book was published in 1596 Linschoten had converted to the Protestant Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This faith celebrated Whitsunday on the same day as Catholics while Saint Helena was marked on 21 May, the same day as the Orthodox Church.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Quite apart from the fact that the discoverers were Catholics, Linschoten failed to realise the impossibility that the island was named after a Protestant feast-day, it being found more than a decade before the Reformation and start of Protestantism.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] An alternative discovery date of 3 May on the Catholic feast-day celebrating the finding of the True Cross by Saint Helena in Jerusalem, as quoted by Odoardo Duarte Lopes in 1591 and by Sir Thomas Herbert in 1638, is suggested as historically more credible than the Protestant date of 21 May.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] News of Cabral's discovery reached Lisbon directly from South America before da Nova's fleet set off on the voyage to India in 1501.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] If da Nova knew the True Cross name had already been assigned, the most obvious and plausible alternative name for him to give the island was "Santa Helena".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The long tradition that João da Nova built a chapel from one of his wrecked carracks has been shown to be based on a misreading of the records.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The **4th Portuguese India Armada** was a Portuguese fleet that sailed from Lisbon in February, 1502.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Along the way, in East Africa, the 4th Armada established a Portuguese factory in present-day Mozambique, made contact and opened trade with the gold entrepot of Sofala and extorted tribute from Kilwa.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Once in India, the armada set about attacking Calicut shipping and disrupting trade along much of the Malabar Coast.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But the ruling Zamorin of Calicut refused to accede to Portuguese demands, arguing that the violent exactions of the armada exceeded any claims they might have for compensation.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The 4th Armada left without bringing the Zamorin to terms and leaving matters unresolved.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Before departing, the armada established a crown factory in Cannanore and left behind a small patrol under Vicente Sodré, the first permanent Portuguese fleet in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Second India Armada, commanded by Pedro Álvares Cabral, had arrived in Portugal in the summer of 1501 in a terrible shape.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Ship and human losses were tremendous, its mission objectives failed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] By the time this news was received, the 3rd India Armada under João da Nova had already departed, a commercial expedition unequipped to deal with the hostile turn of events in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As a result, King Manuel I of Portugal ordered a new fleet to be assembled, the 4th India Armada, armed to the teeth, with the explicit objective of bringing Calicut to heel.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The command of the 4th Armada was offered to Pedro Álvares Cabral.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But various factions in the Portuguese court and the Casa da India, opposed Cabral's appointment, on the grounds that it was Cabral's 'incompetence' that had created this unhappy situation to begin with.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] However, Cabral had his own political supporters that could not be ignored.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Finding this condition an unacceptable affront, Cabral withdrew his name in a huff.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Manuel I immediately appointed Vasco da Gama himself as captain-major.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The intrigues behind the appointment have been variously told.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] By some accounts, the initial offer to Cabral was a *pro forma* gesture to palliate his faction rather than an earnest offer.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] In other words, the king never had any intention of letting Cabral lead the expedition, that the onerous conditions were introduced knowing Cabral would find them unacceptable.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] That these conditions were only revealed at the last minute, just before the fleet's departure, lends credence to the theory, i.e. the monarch did not want to give Cabral time to reconsider or allow opposition to mount against Gama's rapid appointment.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On this hint, Gama produced a royal letter (issued by Manuel back in 1500, and reiterated in October 1501), promising Gama a determining role in any future India expedition, and demanded command of the expedition for himself.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The king was caught between two commitments – honoring the letter to Gama, or his appointment to Cabral.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Hearing of the king's quandary, Cabral voluntarily withdrew his name to graciously allow Manuel I to honor his letter.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The 16th-century chroniclers seem to agree that King Manuel I wanted to deprive Cabral of command, and that the Sodré appointment and/or the Gama letter was just a ploy by the king to wiggle out of appointing Cabral.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But some later authors have interpreted the accounts differently, that King Manuel I was wholly behind Cabral, but was forced to yield to the unsavory machinations of the Gama-Sodré family.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The *vintena* would continue until 1522.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The 4th Armada was composed of 20 ships and between 800 and 1800 men.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Armada was originally envisaged as two squadrons – 15 ships under the admiral to head to India, 5 under the vice-admiral designated to patrol the mouth of the Red Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The exact composition of the three squadrons differs in the various accounts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The following list of ships should not be regarded as authoritative, but a tentative list compiled from various conflicting accounts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] This list of captains is principally based on João de Barros's *Décadas*, Damião de Gois's *Chronica*, Castanheda's *História*, the *Relação das Náos*, Couto's list, Faria e Sousa's *Asia* and Quintella's *Annaes da Marinha*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The list of ship names is from Gaspar Correia's *Lendas da Índia*. and should be suspected as unreliable.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As usual, Correia's list of captains differs significantly from the others.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The anonymous lists of the *Memorias das Armadas* and *Livro de Lisuarte de Abreu* give their own variations.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Doubtless, the captain lists are complicated by the fact that there were some rearrangements of the fleet in Africa and India, and captains were shuffled around – at some point, both Vicente and Brás Sodré was definitely given command of a ship of his own.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The chronicles report that the fleet also carried pre-fabricated lumber and fittings with instructions to assemble a new caravel upon arrival in East Africa.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The most famous ship in the 4th Armada was arguably the one commanded by Estevão da Gama, the *Flor de la Mar* (sometimes spelled as *Frol de la Mar*), a 400 tonne carrack (*nau*), the largest ship of that kind yet built.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The exact sizes of the other large carracks – the flagship *São Jerónimo*, *Lionarda* and the *Leitoa*/*Esmeralda* are unknown, but also presumed to be quite sizeable (that is, 250t or greater).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] These large ships were designated to return with spice cargo back to Lisbon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The smaller naus(*navetas*, 80–120t) and caravels (40–80t), went out as armed fighting ships, to remain as naval patrol vessels in India if necessary.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Gama clan dominated the fleet – Vasco da Gama, his cousin Estêvão da Gama and his uncles Vicente Sodré and Brás Sodré took the leadership positions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] We have assumed Pêro de Ataíde, to be the same person nicknamed 'o Inferno' ('Hell'), a notable veteran captain of Cabral's Second Armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But in some accounts, his name is given as 'Álvaro de Ataíde' a native of the Algarve, thus possibly Vasco da Gama's new brother-in-law (Gama had recently married Catarina de Ataíde in 1500 or 1501; she had a brother by that name).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Lopo Mendes de Vasconcellos was a soon-to-be brother-in-law (betrothed to Teresa da Gama, Vasco's sister).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Among the remaining captains, the most significant was probably *Dom* Luís Coutinho, son of the Count of Marialva, a high nobleman of considerable rank in the Portuguese court.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Diogo Fernandes Correia (archaically, Corrêa) was pre-designated by the Casa da India as the factor for Cochin (replacing the factor Gonçalo Gil Barbosa that Cabral had left there).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] There was significant private participation in the fleet.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Two ships went out under Italian captains – Tomásio da Cremona ('Thomas de Carmona') and Giovanni Buonagrazia ('João da Bonagracia') of Florence.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The *Leitoa Nova* is said to have been privately outfitted by the powerful nobleman Tristão da Cunha in conjunction with the mysterious Lisbon merchant-woman Catarina Dias de Aguiar Eyewitness accounts suggest three more ships were also privately outfitted.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] There were two Italian passengers on the armada – both military engineers, and probably secret Venetian agents – that would play a sinister role in India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They were known by their Portuguese names as João Maria (Gianmaria) and Pêro António (Pierantonio).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Carmona's ship (6) letters dispatched from Lisbon by Italian agents Francesco Corbinelli and Giovanni Francesco Affaitati drawn from interviews with the newly returning crews in August 1503.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The principal mission of the 4th Armada was to settle scores with the Zamorin of Calicut; The armada was to avenge the Zamorin's mistreatment of Cabral and the massacre of the Portuguese in the Calicut factory.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As they did not have enough manpower to conquer Calicut outright, the armada planned to use their first squadron to set up a naval blockade in Calicut harbor, while the second squadron under Vicente Sodré would patrol the Gulf of Aden and cut off all further Arab shipping in the Red Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] This would severely disrupt Calicut's trade and therefore its economic lifeline – a show of force to intimidate the Zamorin into compliance.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Armada would then demand that the Zamorin replace the damaged factory of the 2nd Armada, that he expel all Arabs from the Calicut region as punishment for their involvement in the aforementioned massacre, and that he sign a trade treaty regarding the supply of spice to Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Additionally, 4th Armada was instructed to open trade with the East African city-state of Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Sofala had been secretly visited by the explorer Pêro da Covilhã during his overland expedition back in 1487, and he identified it as the end-point of the Monomatapa gold trade.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Portuguese crown had been eager to tap that gold source, but all prior armadas had failed to find it until Sancho de Tovar, commanding a ship of the 2nd India Armada, had finally located Sofala the previous year, but he only saw it from afar and did not go ashore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] It seems that every ship in this armada was issued explicit royal instructions to try to trade for gold in Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] February 10, 1502, Two squadrons of the 4th Armada – 10 ships under admiral Vasco da Gama and 5 ships under vice-admiral Vicente Sodré– set out from Lisbon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Late February, 1502 – Fleet anchors in Senegal (either at *Porto de Ale* (Sali Portudal) or *Bezeguiche* (Bay of Dakar)) to take water.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] It is reported in one chronicle that Fernan d'Atouguia, captain of the *Leitoa Nova* falls ill and dies here.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama transfers the experienced captain Pedro Afonso de Aguiar from the small nau *Santa Elena* to the large nau *Leitoa Nova*, and elevates one of his own companions, Pêro de Mendonça, to captain Aguiar's old ship.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Early March, 1502 – The 4th Armada sails southwest from Africa and may make a brief watering stop at Cape St.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Augustine (Brazil), before heading across the south Atlantic towards the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] April 1, 1502, The third squadron of the 4th Armada – five ships under Estêvão da Gama – finally sets out from Lisbon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Charting its own course, the third squadron will only catch up with the main body of the 4th Armada in India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] April–May, 1502 Violent storms at the Cape separates the fifteen ships of Vasco da Gama's fleet.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Each captain is forced to figure out his own passage around the Cape, and make his own way towards the pre-arranged rendez-vous point on the other side.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] May, 1502 After making watering stops in Madeira and Cape Verde, Estevão da Gama's third squadron reportedly spots an island in the south Atlantic.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Uncertain which one – could be a Cape Verde island or the Penedo de São Pedro (islets off the Brazilian coast) or even as far as the islands of Trindade and Martim Vaz (further south), but does not stop to investigate.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] (By coincidence, that very same month, the returning Third Armada of João da Nova discovers the island of Saint Helena; despite the timing, the returning fleet will not encounter any of the ships of the outward armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] June 10, 1502 – Chronicles differ on what exactly happens after the first squadrons double the Cape.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Following the account of Gaspar Correia (p.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] 272), Vasco da Gama was among the first ships to arrive in Mozambique Island, the pre-arranged meeting point.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama is immediately recognized by the local sheikh (with whom Gama had a tussle on his first journey back in 1498).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Mozambique ruler immediately offers his pardon for that affair and puts supplies at the disposal of the tempest-tossed Portuguese.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Vasco da Gama remains in Mozambique for a while, waiting for the rest of the battered fleet to trickle in, one by one.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The only known loss is the small nau *Santa Elena*, captained by the novice Pêro de Mendonça, which captured by bad currents around Cape Correntes, ends up running aground near the banks of Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] However the crew is safely rescued by the passing ships of Francisco da Cunha Mareco (*Bretoa*) and Fernão Rodrigues Bardaças (*Santa Marta*).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] With surfeit of crew from the capsized *Santa Elena*, Gama orders the construction of a whole new caravel from scratch on Mozambique Island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Although not mentioned in all sources, the caravel of António do Campo ('Antão Vaz' in Correia), is said to have been badly battered at Cape Correntes, and drifted backwards into Delagoa Bay (Maputo).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Campo will not rejoin the 4th Armada on time for the Indian Ocean crossing, and thus remain stuck in Africa until next year.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] According to Correia, while repairing on Mozambique Island, Vasco da Gama dispatches Pedro Afonso de Aguiar (captain of the *Leitoa*) and two caravels south to the city of Sofala, the entrepot of the Monomatapa gold trade.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Sofala had been missed by all prior armadas, but not this time.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Following up on the scout report of Sancho de Tovar from the previous year (see 2nd India Armada), Aguiar leads the first Portuguese ships into Sofala harbor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Aguiar goes ashore, initiates some trade in the local markets while seeking out the local ruler, the sultan or shiekh Isuf of Sofala (*Yçuf* in Barros; *Çufe* in Goes).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] An audience is arranged and Aguiar draws up a commercial and alliance treaty between Portugal and Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Matters settled and gifts exchanged, Aguiar takes aboard a Sofalese ambassador to meet Vasco da Gama back in Mozambique.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] In other accounts, (principally Osório (p.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] 192), mildly corroborated by other chroniclers and the anonymous Portuguese eyewitness and Matteo da Bergamo) it is Vasco da Gama himself, and not Aguiar, who goes to Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] After accounting for all the ships and sending them on to Mozambique, Vasco da Gama himself sailed south with four ships to Sofala, conducted some trade and opened the first contact with the Sofalese ruler.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] That would mean Gama was the last to arrive in Mozambique.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] In this alternative account, the lost ship of Mendonça (or Fernandes) was one of the four that went with Gama to Sofala, and capsized while exiting the Sofala banks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Late June, 1502 – Vasco da Gama makes arrangements to leave Mozambique.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] A Portuguese factory is established on Mozambique Island, with Gonçalo Baixo as the factor, with some ten assistants, to capitalize on the results of the Sofala trade mission.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The new caravel finished, Gama christens it *Pomposa* and places it, together with some 30 crew, under the command of João Serrão (of future Magellan fame), with instructions to take any goods from the Sofalese trade.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] According to Correia, Gama was unwilling to wait around for the results of Aguiar's mission to Sofala, and set sail out of Mozambique before Aguiar's returned from Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As a result, Aguiar was forced to leave the Sofalese ambassador in Mozambique (letting him find his own way back home) and set sail for Malindi, hoping to catch Gama there.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama had gone first to Kilwa (*Quiloa*).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The dominant city-state on the East African coast, Kilwa Sultanate was the formal overlord of Mozambique and Sofala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] If the fledgling Portuguese trade presence in those East African towns was to remain unmolested, then the Portuguese must secure Kilwa's consent.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Cabral and the 2nd Armada had tried, and failed, to secure a treaty with Kilwa back in 1500.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama decided to try again – and was determined not to take no for answer.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But, mindful of the lesson at Calicut, Gama also wanted to add a touch of intimidation, to show off his heavily armed fleet and impress upon the Sultan of Kilwa the consequences of interfering or turning back on any agreement.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On July 12, 1502, Gama's large, menacing armada arrived at the island-city of Kilwa.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama sent for the Kilwa ruler, Emir Ibrahim, inviting him aboard the *São Jeronimo*, to negotiate a treaty of peace and trade.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Sensing a trap, Emir Ibrahim first asks for a safe-conduct (which da Gama promptly gives him), but fearing treachery, the emir changes his mind, and refuses to go aboard.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] However, after much discussion, one of his advisors, a certain wealthy nobleman Muhammad ibn Rukn ad Din (called Muhammad Arcone or Ancone or Enconij by the chroniclers ) finally persuades the emir to take up the Portuguese offer.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Emir Ibrahim is ferried to the flagship and climbs aboard.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] After minimal opening cordialities, and ostentatious proclamations of friendship, Gama lays down his price: a treaty with Portugal has to be paid for with a hefty cash tribute to the King of Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Declaring tribute to be a dishonor, he refuses.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama threatens to level the city and lay it to fire and waste.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Emir Ibrahim, effectively captive on board, reluctantly agrees, and signs a treaty making Kilwa tributary to Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Leaving the Kilwan nobleman and advisor Muhammad Arcone aboard as a hostage, the emir returns to shore to make the arrangements.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] mid-July, 1502 – After a few days of lingering in Kilwa harbor and no sign of the emir's promised tribute, Gama dispatches a messenger to see what the delay is.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Emir Ibrahim sends a message back declining to dispatch the tribute, and telling the Portuguese captain-major that he can do whatever he will with the hostage Muhammad Arcone, given that his poor counsel had proven him unworthy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The angry Gama throws Arcone into a long-boat, without water or shade, to die of heat and exposure.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Nonetheless, Muhammad Arcone is a wealthy man in his own right, and servants from his household offer Gama a substantial ransom to release him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Knowing the hostage is otherwise worthless to him, Gama consents.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] July 20, 1502 – His vengeance on Muhammad Arcone's bad counsel satisfied, the Emir Ibrahim of Kilwa finally decides to send some tribute – some 1500 gold *meticals* – to satisfy the Portuguese captain-major.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Vasco da Gama, anxious not to miss the monsoon winds to India, takes what he can get.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] [The extorted gold coins of Kilwa were used by the goldsmith Gil Vicente in 1506 to make the famous gold pyx or monstrance known as the *Custódia de Belém*, for the Jerónimos Monastery in Belém.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] 282) reports a little knot before departing: several dozen Kilwan women 'picked up' (read: abducted) and taken aboard the ships by bored Portuguese sailors for fun and amusement refuse to return ashore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Although Emir Ibrahim promises that they will be unharmed, he cannot guarantee that those who allowed themselves to be baptized Christian by enthusiastic chaplains on the ships will be taken back by their families.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] July 15, 1502, In the meantime, part of the third squadron, the trio that held with Estêvão da Gama (Gama, Dias, Carmona) arrive at Mozambique Island, half-famished and heavily damaged.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] At that same time, the remaining pair (Vasconcellos, Buonagrazia) alight at the Sofala banks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The two squads do not reconnect with each other.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Estêvão da Gama's trio, following the itinerary left in Mozambique by his cousin, heads off to Kilwa Alone idling before Sofala, Vasconcellos and Buonagrazia proceed north to the mouth of the *Rio de Bons Sinaes* (Zambezi River), where they put in for repairs and recuperation.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On July 23, 1502, part of the third squad (Estêvão da Gama, Lopo Dias and Thomas de Carmona) arrived in Kilwa, just in time to reconnect the main armada of Vasco da Gama, preparing to depart from Kilwa harbor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] At that moment (July 22 actually), the remaining two ships of the third squad (Vasconcellos, Buonagrazia) finally arrive in Mozambique Island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Taking note of the notes and itinerary left behind, they set sail for Malindi, hoping to catch the main fleet there.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Late July, 1502 – Vasco da Gama arrives in Malindi, just in time to be met by Pedro Afonso de Aguiar (from Sofala), who reports to him the results of the Sofala treaty.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama's fleet does not actually dock in Malindi – they intended to, but miss it, landing a few leagues ahead, unable to turn back because of the weather (although they manage to get some supplies and exchange messages with Malindi emissaries that row out to them).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On July 29, 1502, Vasco da Gama's fleet departed its anchorage near Malindi for its Indian Ocean crossing.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] He was missing three ships: *Campo*, *Vasconcelos* and *Buonagrazia*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] August 2, 1502 – The remaining two ships of the third squadron (Lopo Mendes de Vasconcelos and Giovanni Buonagrazia) arrive in Malindi, just a few days after Gama's departure.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They are well received by the Sultan of Malindi.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They pick up a few letters left with degredado Luiz da Moura in Malindi by the returning fleet of João da Nova a few months earlier, reporting the latest Indian news.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They do not stay long, but immediately set sail after Gama's fleet.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The last missing ship – António do Campo's caravel from the first squadron – will not make it across to India this year.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As already alluded to earlier, the caravel of António do Campo ('Antão Vaz' in Correia) is said to have been caught up and battered by bad winds at Cape Correntes and forced to drift with the current of the Mozambique Channel aimlessly southwest.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Campo's caravel is said to have alighted at Delagoa Bay (now Maputo Bay).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The hitherto unknown capacious bay is watered by three rivers: the Maputo river to the south, the Espirito Santo 'river' to the west (actually an estuary formed by the Umbeluzi, Matola and Tembe rivers) and the Maniça (now Incomati) river to the north.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Being told by the local inhabitants that the Espírito Santo 'river' was sourced from a great lake deep in the interior, Campo names it *Rio da Lagoa* (River of the Lagoon), from which we get the name by which Maputo Bay was long known: 'Delagoa Bay'.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Having been forced to linger at Delagoa for repairs, António do Campo hurries north to try to make junction with the rest of the 4th Armada at Malindi, but arrives too late (mid-September).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The fleet having already left for India, and the monsoon winds preventing Campo's own crossing to India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] António do Campo will remain behind on the East African coast until next April.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] mid-August, 1502 – After its Indian Ocean crossing, the 4th Armada alights near the opulent port of Dabul (north of Goa).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] These are the territorial waters of the powerful Muslim sultan Adil Shah (*Hidalcão*) of Bijapur.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Expecting trouble, the fighting ships hoist up their lateen sails and load up their cannon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But no one comes out to challenge them, so they begin coasting south along the Indian coast towards Kerala.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] August 20, 1502 Gama's fleet reaches Anjediva island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The next day, the ships of Giovanni Buonagrazia (carrying Thomé Lopes) and Lopo Mendes de Vasconcellos (*Juiloa*) finally catch up with the rest of the armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Save for the ship of Campo (still stuck in Africa) and Serrão (on patrol around the Mozambique factory), all the Portuguese fleet (18 ships out of the 20 that left Lisbon) are together and accounted for.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Around Anjediva island, the armada spots three boats belonging to Timoja, the Hindu privateer who operates out of Honnavar (*Onor*), on the frontline between the warring states of Muslim Bijapur and Hindu Vijayanagar.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They give chase unto the mouth of the Sharavathi River, at which point the pirate boats slip into harbor of Onor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Assured by Gaspar da Gama (Goese Jew and translator) that Onor is a corsair's nest, Vasco da Gama orders an attack on the city.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese landing crews attack the harbor, plundering and setting fire to the ships and docks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The day after the raid on Onor, the 4th Armada arrives at the mouth of the river that leads up to the city of Bhatkal (*Batecala*), south of Onor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Perceiving what he considers hostile gestures from shore, the captain-major dispatches his cousin, Estêvão da Gama upriver to the town to investigate.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Surveying the Batecala docks, Estêvão spies several Arab merchant ships and prepares for hostilities.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But his attention is soon drawn to a small group of men in ornate robes, rushing down to the docks, frantically calling to him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It is an embassy from the raja of Batecala, requesting an immediate audience with the Portuguese captain-major.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Estêvão brings the embassy to his cousin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Evidently hearing of the fate of Onor, the embassy offers to submit to the Portuguese.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vasco da Gama agrees to leave Batecala in peace in return for a yearly tribute of 1,000 bags of plain rice and 500 bags of quality rice (probably Basmati).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Batecala is also to agree to the exclusion of the Arab merchants from the city, that no pepper trade is to be carried at this port, and that no ship be allowed to travel between Batecala and Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The treaty is set down in writing and signed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Late August/Early September 1502 – Business in Batecala done, Vasco da Gama sets sail towards Cannanore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They anchor in around Mount d'Eli, the common touch-point for ships on the Jedda-Calicut route, evidently intending to catch some prizes before proceeding.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] September 29, 1502 – After prowling around Mt. d'Eli for nearly a month with little success (they captured only one minor ship), captain Gil Matoso (on the *São Gabriel*), spots a large merchant ship carrying Muslim pilgrims returning from Mecca (or going to it, chronicles contradict).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The ship, the *Miri*, is identified as belonging to a certain al-Fanqi, one of wealthier men of Calicut and said by some to be the Meccan factor in Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Matoso chases the pilgrim ship down, which surrenders rather quickly, probably imagining that its master had enough money to ransom it off.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vasco da Gama shrugs off all the offers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As the Portuguese crew plunder the ship and transfer its cargo, it quickly becomes evident that Gama intends to burn the ship with all its passengers – men, women and children – on board.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] When Gama proves deaf to their pleas for mercy, the passengers frantically attack the Portuguese men-at-arms with their bare hands, to no avail.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 3, 1502 – a day, eyewitness Thomé Lopes states, "I will never forget for the rest of my days".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The pilgrim ship thoroughly plundered, on Gama's orders, the passengers are locked in the hold and the ship burnt and sunk by artillery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It takes several days to finally go down completely.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese soldiers row around the waters on longboats mercilessly spearing survivors.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The sinking of the *Miri* is an act that will instantly cement Gama's cruel and fearsome reputation, and generate a great deal of hatred for the Portuguese in India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama defended his act as "vengeance" for the Calicut massacre of 1500, arguing that the ship's owner, as a prominent person in Calicut, was 'doubtlessly' responsible for the sinister counsel to the Zamorin that led up to it.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Of the eyewitnesses, all mention it, but only Thomé Lopes openly condemns the act, claiming Gama acted "with great cruelty and without any mercy whatsoever".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The chroniclers do not shy away from describing the event and their unease is evident.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Although Barros and Castanheda reiterate Gama's justification of the act as revenge for Cabral, they do not seem to embrace it themselves.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Indeed, Barros, Góis and Osório claim the ship belonged to the Sultan of Egypt, who was in no way responsible for the events in Calicut, thus subtly suggesting Gama may have made a mistake.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gaspar Correia is a little more open in his disapproval.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He notes that several of the Portuguese captains were appalled by Gama's decision and tried to persuade him against it (if only because they would forego a hefty ransom).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Correia gives a heart-rending account of the desperate and valiant resistance of the doomed passengers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Poet Luís de Camões passes over the incident in silence, evidently feeling it detrimental to the heroic portrait of Vasco da Gama.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Estimates of those killed on the *Miri* hover around 300.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese chroniclers are eager to report that 20 children were spared this fate, and brought back by the 4th Armada to Lisbon, where they will be baptized and raised as friars at the Nossa Senhora de Belém.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Among the eyewitnesses Thomé Lopes and the anonymous Flemish sailor make no mention of this small mercy, although Matteo de Bergamo does point it out.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 18, 1502 – Vasco da Gama's armada finally reaches Cannanore (*Canonor*, Kannur), and delivers the Cannanore ambassador that had gone to Lisbon with Cabral's 2nd Armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore invites Gama to come ashore for an elaborate reception, but Gama replies that he swore a personal oath not to set his foot on Indian soil again until his vengeance on Calicut was sated.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As a result, the rajah orders a wooden scaffold to be built over the seashore, where they can meet in person without violating the vow.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama presents the raja with royal letters and munificent gifts (a jeweled sword, a brocaded armchair) and discussions immediately begin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] A commercial treaty is negotiated, establishing a Portuguese crown factory in Cannanore, and arranging a fixed-price schedule, which the Raja personally guarantees, for the sale of spices to the Portuguese.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The negotiation for the commercial treaty did not go smoothly, particularly the fixed price clause.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Kolathiri Raja protested that he had no power over market prices nor the right to dictate how private merchants disposed of their property.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama had to resort to feints, threats and then sailed out of Cannanore in anger.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Barros credits the role of Paio Rodrigues, the Portuguese factor (private, not crown, an employee of the private employee of D. Álvaro of Braganza and the Marchionni consortium), that had been left behind in Cannanore by João da Nova's Third Armada at the beginning of the year.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Correia points out this is the treaty where the Portuguese *cartaz* system was first introduced.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Henceforth, every merchant ship along the Malabar coast had to present a certificate signed by a Portuguese factor (in Cannanore, Cochin, etc.), or else be subject to attack and seizure by a Portuguese patrol.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] This licensing system would be subsequently adopted later on other Portuguese-controlled coasts (e.g.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] East Africa, Malacca, Brazil), with differing degrees of success.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It will be largely maintained until the 18th century.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 25, 1502 – Fleet departs Cannanore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Chroniclers differ a little on the subsequent sequence of events.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] While still in Cannanore, Gama had sent Pedro Afonso de Aguiar to Calicut in advance, with the warning that he had come to settle scores for the mistreatment of Cabral and to get compensation for the overrunning of the Calicut factory in 1500.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In response, the Zamorin of Calicut sent back a string of messengers to Cannanore (and along the way to Calicut), each delivering promises that the Zamorin was willing to settle matters with Gama, and compensate the Portuguese for the loss of their factory goods.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 29, 1502 – Gama's large armada finally arrives before the harbor of Calicut (*Calecute*, Kozhikode).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin dispatches an emissary, a Brahmin (dressed as a Christian friar) on a boat to Gama.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama is angered, feeling that the Zamorin has changed his tone from his earlier messages, and demands the property taken from the factory be restored in full and brought to his ship, and that all Muslim merchants must be expelled from the Calicut, before any discussion about a treaty begins.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] While awaiting the Zamorin's reply, Gama seizes a nearby idling zambuq and some fishing boats that had unwisely ventured into Calicut harbor, taking some fifty fisherman captive.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] This action evidently angers the Zamorin, who sends a stern reply to Gama, noting that Gama had already taken severalfold times more property from Calicut ships, and slaughtered ten times more of his citizens (on the *Miri*, etc.) than the Portuguese lost in the 1500 riot.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Despite being the net sufferer and the clamor of his citizens for revenge, the Zamorin is prepared to forgive and forget and start anew.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin also replies that Calicut is a free port and he has no intention of expelling 'the Moors'.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 31, 1502 – Infuriated by the reply, Gama sends out a strongly worded ultimatum, declaring that the Zamorin's permission means nothing to him, that he has until noon the next day to deliver the Portuguese factory goods to his ship.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama uses this overnight interlude to send his boats out to sound the harbor of Calicut to find optimal firing positions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] That same night, Calicut forces set about frantically digging entrenchments, erecting a protective timber palisade and laying cannon along the harbor shore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 1, 1502 – At noon, having received no reply, Gama orders that his Malabari prisoners be strung up by their necks from the shipmasts, allocating a few to each ship.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Calicut crowds approach the beach to watch the grisly spectacle.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Then the armada advances into the harbor and opens fire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The bombardment is principally aimed at clearing the beach and trenches.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Malabari shore cannons are too few, their range and power too weak, to provide an effective reply.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The bombardment continues until nightfall.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] That night, the corpses of the hung Malabaris are taken from masts, their feet and hands severed off and sent by a small boat to the beach, with an insulting message to the Zamorin, including a demand that the Zamorin reimburse the Portuguese for the powder and shot expended on destroying his city.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 2, 1502 – The city bombardment resumes the next morning.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The mostly poor dwellings on the shore having been razed the previous day, the Portuguese cannons now have a clear view of central city and the statelier homes of the richer citizens of Calicut and bring their larger ordnance to bear.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The city is relentlessly bombarded all morning – some 400 large rounds and an indeterminate number from the smaller caliber guns At noon, when the Portuguese pause for lunch, a small group of Malabari vessels tries to attack the idling squad, but are quickly seen off.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 3, 1502 – Barros reports that the two-day bombardment had sufficiently crippled the city that several of the captains urge Gama to authorize a landing of troops to sack Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Gama, still hopeful the Zamorin might come to terms, turns down their request, believing a sack would only escalate matters to the point of no return.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] So, the next morning, vengeance satisfied, Gama sets sail out of Calicut harbor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Seizing the convoy, Gama orders the cargoes transferred, the crews tied, their teeth beaten out, their noses and hands cut off and the ships set alight.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The violent treatment meted out by Vasco da Gama sends shockwaves throughout the Malabar coast.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Merchant ships in Indian ports hurriedly leave the area or go into concealment.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] All shipping along the coast essentially freezes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Before leaving Calicut, Gama assembles a squadron of five or six fighting ships under Vicente Sodré and his brother Brás Sodré, with some 200 soldiers (mainly crossbowmen), to maintain the blockade on Calicut harbor, and patrol the coast preying on Calicut shipping.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The exact composition of the patrol squadron differs in the sources, and it seems there is some reshuffling of captains in the process.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The patrol squadron captains are taken from the lists in Castanheda, Góis and Osório Other sources are not so explicit.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The ship names are tentatively deduced from Gaspar Correia, who, as usual, deviates in naming the captains.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 3, 1502, His blockade of Calicut in place, Vasco da Gama arrives in Cochin (*Cohim*, Kochi) with the bulk of the armada.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He is received by Trimumpara ruler of Cochin, not without a touch of anxiety.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Nair hostage taken accidentally by the 2nd Armada the previous year is delivered, along with the letter of the other Nair who stayed back in Lisbon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama concludes negotiates a new commercial treaty with the ruler of Cochin, this time with a fixed-price schedule, like at Cannanore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Diogo Fernandes Correia, the new designated factor for Cochin, relieves Cabral's factor Gonçalo Gil Barbosa (now slated to be transferred to Cannanore).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They promptly set about their business of buying spices and loading ships in Cochin for the return journey.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] While conducting business at Cochin, Vasco da Gama receives a letter from the queen-regent of Quilon (*Coulão*, Kollam), on behalf of her young son, the raja Govardhana Martanda.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The queen invites the Portuguese fleet to load up with spices at Quilon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama declines politely, noting that he cannot do anything without the permission of his Cochinese hosts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As a result, the queen-regent dispatches a messenger to the prince of Cochin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Trimumpara Raja prevaricates at first, fearing that competition from Quilon's more amply supplied markets will hurt his own.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Cochin's slender supply is worrying the Portuguese factors.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] At length, an agreement is reached between all parties: Gama is to dispatch only two ships to load up with spices at Quilon, and promises not to set up a permanent factory in that city.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The two ships, carrying temporary factor João de Sá Pereira, the first Portuguese to enter Quilon, will load up quickly, and return to Cochin within ten days.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 19, 1502 – While at Cochin, Gama receives a message from Syrian Christian community of nearby Cranganore offering to place themselves under the protection of the King of Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama accepts their gift of a red silver-tipped sceptre, a symbolic command staff, but notes that he personally cannot do much, as he will be leaving soon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But he promises that the community can call on the Portuguese naval patrol of Vicente Sodré at any time, should they need anything.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] January 3, 1503 – A wealthy Brahmin, accompanied by his son and nephew, shows up Cochin and requests permission from Vasco da Gama to take passage on the 4th Armada to Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama assures him he is fully empowered by the king, at which point the Brahmin then offers to mediate a peace treaty between Gama and the Zamorin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama agrees, and the Brahmin returns to Calicut, coming back to Cochin shortly after accompanied by a Nair of the Zamorin's household, with a concrete offer to compensate the Portuguese for the goods lost in the Calicut factory.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It seems a fair offer, so Gama decides to personally finalize the arrangement.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] January 5, 1503 – Vasco da Gama takes his cousin's ship, the *Frol de la Mar*, plus one caravel, to carry the Brahmin and the Nair back to Calicut, to finalize the peace treaty with the Zamorin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama leaves the rest of the 4th Armada in Cochin under D.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] (Rumors of the imminent peace with Calicut angers the merchants of Cochin, who feel they will be short-changed by any agreement with Calicut; Coutinho has a difficult time securing the continued purchasing and loading of spices).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama is taking only a light escort, but he imagines Vicente Sodré is in the vicinity and will provide additional security.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] However, as it happens, Vicente Sodré had left Calicut a few days earlier.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He had been maintaining a continuous blockade on Calicut harbor, and engaging in repeated cat-and-mouse chases with small Calicut fishing ships that dared venture out.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] At one point, Sodré gave a couple of fishing boats chase into a side-channel, and sailed into a trap – forty armed Calicut paraus quickly surrounded him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] A lucky cannon shot on the lead ship broke up the ambush, allowing Sodré to extricate himself from there quickly.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He sailed out and raced back to Cannanore to pick up the rest of his patrol.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama arrives in Calicut harbor during this absence, unaware of any of this.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Seeing no sign of Sodré, Gama orders the escort caravel to go towards Cannanore to find him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He anchors his own ship, the large *Flor de la Mar*, inside the harbor and lowers a skiff to take the Brahmin to shore, to meet the Zamorin and arrange for the delivery of the compensation payment, retaining the Brahmin's two relatives and the Nair on board as hostages.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Three days are spent waiting, the Brahmin shuttling back and forth between the ship and the shore repeatedly to report and consult on the progress of the negotiations.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] All seemed to be going well, but in the early morning hours of the fourth day, however, a hundred armed zambuks and paraus swarm into the harbor from the nearby channels and quickly surround the *Flor de la Mar*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The *Flor'*s high sides do not allow the Portuguese to respond with artillery – the ship's cannons are mounted too high and the paraus are too close for an angle of shot, so the crew turns desperately to crossbows, musket fire and heaving rocks to keep them at bay.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Days before the encounter, Gama had captured a large parau, which was now tied to the stern of the *Flor*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In the heat of the fighting, Malabari sappers row up to the tied parau, fill it with tinder, set it afire, and direct the flaming ship towards the *Flor*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama immediately orders the cables cut and the flames of the drifting parau only just miss them.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Throughout all this, some of the Portuguese sailors are desperately trying to cut the cables on the anchor – a process that took time, as Gama had ordered it down with an iron chain.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But eventually the anchor is cut, and the *Flor* begins to sail away.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As distance is gained from the zambuks and paraus, the ship's cannons can now come into play and fire on the pursuers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The *Flor* reaches the mouth of the harbor just as Vicente Sodré arrives back from Cannanore with three caravels.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Seeing the ambush is foiled, the Calicut boats turn around and slip back into the side-channels of the harbor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Before leaving Calicut, Gama orders the three hostages – the son & nephew of the Brahmin and the Nair – strung up by their necks on the main mast, in full view of the city of Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He dispatches their corpses on a raft to the shore, pinned with a note swearing revenge on the Zamorin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] After the ambush, Gama, escorted by Sodré's patrol returns to Cochin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The assembled Calicut fleet is estimated at 20 large ships, 40 gun-mounted *sambuks* (large dhows) and an innumerable number of smaller oar-powered paraus, carrying several thousand armed men.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Trimumpara Raja of Cochin urges Gama to avoid the fleet and just set sail for Portugal at once.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vasco da Gama refuses to revise his plans.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He needs to return to Cannanore to deposit the factor Barbosa there and pick up a cargo of ginger he had ordered.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] And he was itching for revenge for the ambush.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They are soon joined by Sodré's caravel squadron, and set sail warily towards Cannanore, guns ready for the Calicut ambush.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama and Sodré spot the Calicut fleet of Coja Casem and Arab privateer Cojambar, near the coast, out of Calicut harbor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Although the Arab squadron is out of commission too soon, Coja Casem nonetheless proceeds forward with his fleet of Malabari sambuks, hoping to use their speed to outmaneuver the guns of the heavy-laden naus and reach for the grapple.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Gama sends the escort caravels under Vicente Sodré to intercept them in their tracks, while the cargo naus hurry on toward Cannanore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Although the caravels are outnumbered, it is not much of a battle.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The fight is essentially over when Pero Rafael and Gil Matoso quickly board and capture Coja Casem's flagship (oddly, found with a lot of women and children on board).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Calicut fleet breaks up and rushes back to port.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The pursuing caravels capture a number of sambuks, which they proceed to tow and set on fire before Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The long-prepared ambush has been foiled.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Danger dispelled, the caravels proceed to Cannanore to make junction with the main fleet.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Battle of Calicut, like the previous year's naval battle of Cannanore, once again demonstrated the critical importance of the technical superiority of Portuguese ships and naval artillery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But it also demonstrated to the Portuguese that the Zamorin of Calicut was not as easy to intimidate as they had expected.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Despite the terror actions, the bombardment and the naval blockade, the Zamorin steadfastly refused to capitulate to Vasco da Gama's terms.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] On the contrary, the hiring of an Arab privateer fleet demonstrated a certain resourcefulness and willingness to continue fighting and take the fight to the Portuguese.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The hiring of Cojambar was also a foreboding.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin clearly understood he had to appeal to foreigners to help close the technical gap between Indian and Portuguese forces.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Surely it would only be a matter of time before the Zamorin got his hands on Arab, Turkish and Venetian technology, and more substantial support from these great powers than just a Red Sea pirate or two?
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] If the battle of Calicut impressed something on Vasco da Gama, it was precisely that the Portuguese in India were living on borrowed time, that it was going to take more resources than he had to bring the Zamorin to heel and secure continued Portuguese access to the spice markets.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] And that was the message he would bring back to Lisbon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In the meantime, his priority was to do everything he could to maintain the Portuguese toe in India - that is, to protect the Portuguese factories and Indian allies of Cochin and Cannanore, from the Zamorin's inevitable revenge the moment the 4th Armada left.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Arriving in Cannanore, Gama leaves Cabral's old factor Gonçalo Gil Barbosa, and two assistants, Bastião Álvares and Diogo Nunes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] With the permission of the Kolithiri Raja of Cannanore, Gama erects a small palisade around the factory.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Some 200 armed men (others report merely 20) are to remain with the factory.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] More troubling, however, is the India patrol squadron.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Back in Lisbon, Vicente Sodré had been given a commission (*regimento*) by king Manuel I of Portugal instructing him to lead a patrol of five or six caravels in the Gulf of Aden, and prey on the rich Arab prizes going in and out of the Red Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vasco da Gama, realizing the vulnerability of Cochin and Cannanore, invokes rank as captain-major of the armada and orders Sodré to set that mission aside, and maintain his patrol on the Indian coast, to defend the Portuguese factories and their Indian allies against any reaction by the Zamorin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The return journey is quick and relatively smooth, with only one stop in Mozambique Island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It is caught in a slight storm around the Cape, where Estêvão da Gama's *Flor da la Mar* parts company from the rest.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Estêvão da Gama, making his way back to Lisbon by himself, is said to have stumbled upon the South Atlantic islands of Saint Helena (already discovered the previous year by João da Nova's Third Armada).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vasco da Gama's main fleet arrives in Lisbon in September, 1503.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama delivers his report, noting his failure to bring the Zamorin of Calicut to terms, and urging the immediate outfitting of a strong fleet to establish strong permanent Portuguese garrisons to protect the allied cities of Cochin and Cannanore.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama arrives too late to affect the outfitting of the 5th Armada, which had already departed in April, 1503 under the command of Afonso de Albuquerque.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But his recommendation will guide the formation of the next one, the 6th Armada, set to sail in the Spring of 1504 under the command of Lopo Soares de Albergaria.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] March, 1503 – As soon as Vasco da Gama's 4th Armada leaves India, as predicted, Raja Trimumpara of Cochin receives intelligence that the Zamorin of Calicut is at this very moment preparing a landward invasion of Cochin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese factor Diogo Fernandes Correia urges Vicente Sodré to keep the caravel patrol squadron close to Cochin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vicente Sodré, eager for the easy plunder of the Arab Red Sea shipping, dismisses the rumors, Correia reminds him of Gama's orders, to no avail – Sodré pulls out his old royal *regimento* and orders the coastal patrol to follow him out to the Red Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It is said that at least two of the captains of the coastal patrol refuse Sodré's orders, and willingly surrender the command of their ships rather than disobey Gama's original orders.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The composition of the patrol that set out to the Red Sea varies in different accounts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] One arrangement is that it was six ships: 1.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vicente Sodré first sets out north to Gujarat, where it captures a great merchant ship off Chaul.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The patrol then sails west into the Gulf of Aden, at the mouth of the Red Sea, to catch more prizes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] About five Arab merchant ships are seized by the patrol there but, according to the account written later by Pêro de Ataíde, the Sodré brothers set about claiming a disproportionate share of the plunder for themselves, including embezzling the royal fifth.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In Ataíde's account, Brás Sodré appears as the villain of the story.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Already unhappy at the decision to abandon their comrades in India, the patrol captains quarreled with the Sodré brothers and nearly mutinied.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In late April, the patrol anchored in at Kuria Muria islands (off the coast of Oman).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The local inhabitants warned them that a seasonal tempest was forming and that they had better move their ships to a safer shelter on the southern side of the island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Four patrol captains moved their ships accordingly, but Vicente Sodré and Brás Sodré refused (the ongoing quarrel over the spoils may have been a factor in this decision.) As the locals predicted, the tempest came, destroyed and sunk the ships of Vicente Sodré and Brás Sodré.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Mearns of BWR and Oman's Ministry of Heritage and Culture.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In the aftermath, the four remaining ships of the coastal patrol, who elected of Pêro de Ataíde as their new commander, set back for India.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] However, contrary winds make it a difficult journey, and they inch back only painfully and slowly.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The battered patrol hobbles into Angediva island sometime in the summer of 1503, where they are forced to stop to repair their crippled ships.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Four days after arriving in Angediva, a fifth ship, the caravel of António do Campo (who having missed the previous year's monsoon, was forced to stay in East Africa throughout all this) arrives in Anjediva and joins the patrol.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They are still repairing at Angediva when the ships of Francisco de Albuquerque and Nicolau Coelho, the vanguard of the 5th Armada, arrives in India in August, 1503.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] April 1503 – Not long after the Sodré patrol departed for the Red Sea, the Zamorin of Calicut arrived with his 50,000-strong army at *Repelim* (Edapalli), on the boundaries of the Cochinese state.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He demanded that the Raja Trimumpara of Cochin hand his Portuguese guests over to him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Trimumpara refused and his son Narayan repels two Calicut assaults.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] By bribery and deceit, the Zamorin manages to detach a lot of Cochin's army, overwhelms the defenses and kills prince Narayan at a battle near the Edapalli ford.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Trimumpara Raja and his Portuguese guests (factor Diogo Fernandes Correia and his assistants), accompanied by a small loyal Nair guard, abandon Cochin city and flee across the harbor to Vypin, a barrier island of the Vembanad lagoon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vypin's natural defenses and the deteriorating weather prevent the Zamorin from launching assault boats and seizing the island.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Frustrated, the Zamorin burns down the city of Cochin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The siege will drag on for several months, until Francisco de Albuquerque, leading the remnant of the Sodré patrol, hurrying down from Angediva, arrived in Cochin in August–September, and forced the Calicut forces to withdraw.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Expert gun-founders, the Italians will teach Calicut to found large European guns and help close the technological gap between Indian and Portuguese artillery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin of Calicut, before burning down Cochin, removed an ancient sacred stone, upon which the ancient Kings of Malabar (see Chera Dynasty) were traditionally ceremonially esconsed as lords of the sea and overlords of all the Malabari states.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The sacred stone had originally been housed at the ancient Malabari capital of Cranganore, but had since been moved to Cochin.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin now moved it once more, to Edapalli.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Abraham Willaerts was born in Utrecht, the son of the painter Adam Willaerts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He trained with his father, a marine painter.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He later studied with the Utrecht Caravaggist Jan van Bijlert in Utrecht.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He became a member of the Utrecht Guild of Saint Luke in 1624.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He travelled to Paris in 1628 where he worked in the workshop of the prominent religious and history painter Simon Vouet.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He returned to his home country in 1635.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] On 1637 or 1638 Willaerts sailed to Brazil serving in the entourage of Count John Maurice of Nassau-Siegen, the governor of the Dutch possessions in Brazil.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] In 1641 the Count sent him with the Dutch fleet from Brazil to Angola (where the Dutch had just taken São Paulo de Loanda and the island of Tomé) on a mission to observe the customs and manners of the indigenous people.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Among the paintings he produced were portraits of King Garcia II of Kongo, and Njinga Mbande, the famous queen of Ndongo and Matamba then allied with the Dutch against the Portuguese.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Willaerts was also probably responsible for the content, if not the execution of the illustrations of Central Africa that appear in Olfert Dapper's geographical book Description of Africa (1668 book).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He had returned to the Netherlands in 1644, where he stayed with the prominent architect and painter Jacob van Campen at his castle Randenbroeck near Amersfoort.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Here he joined the Bentvueghels, an association of mainly Dutch and Flemish artists working in Rome.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] It was customary for the Bentvueghels to adopt an appealing nickname, the so-called 'bent name'.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Abraham Willaerts was reportedly given the bent name 'Indian'.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] This nickname was likely given him because of his travels among the Brazilian tribes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He probably travelled further south to Naples, where he may have found inspiration for his imaginary views of Mediterranean ports.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] His brother Isaac was also a marine painter.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Although mainly a marine painter, Willaerts also painted portraits.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] His marine paintings closely follow those of his father as is seen in his *Ships near a rocky shore* (1647, Frans Hals Museum, Haarlem).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He preferred compositions with an atmospheric softness.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] In addition to Dutch harbour and coastal scenes, he also painted Mediterranean harbour views (real and imaginary), such as the Harbour of Naples (National Maritime Museum, London).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Despite Willaerts' six-year stay in Brazil and in Angola his compositions never treated specifically Brazilian or African subjects.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Willaerts painted a series of portraits, both of single figures (several were admirals) and family groups.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] He also added portraits in the foreground of some of his father's harbour scenes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abraham-willaerts] Willaerts also collaborated with the still life painter Willem Ormea on a *Fish still life with stormy sea* which combines a seascape with a still life of fish in the foreground.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The **Achaemenid navy** (Old Persian: 𐎴𐎠𐎺 *nāva*) was the principal naval force of the Achaemenid Empire which existed between 525 BC and 330 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] In Old Persian, the written language of Achaemenid inscriptions, the word used to refer to the 'navy' or 'fleet' was "*nāva*", a noun in plural feminine nominative form.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] It is of the same root of Indo-European for words such as "navy" and "navigate".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] In modern usage of Persian language, the word has retained its form and meaning (lit.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] No relevant primary documents have been found about it, nor have any ruins of Persian naval installations or remains of ships been excavated.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] While independent Persian tradition is lost, all we know about the Achaemenid navy is recorded by ancient Greek historians like Herodotus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Scholars categorize the record of operation of the navy to two distinct periods from 525 to 479, and from 479 to 330 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Cambyses founded the navy for conquest of Egypt in the Battle of Pelusium.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] After him, Darius I deployed the navy to strengthen dominance over the coast of Asia Minor, as well as its adjacent islands.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] During reign of Darius, Persians captured Samos (c.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] 517 BC), conquered Thrace, waged war on Scythia (c.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] 512 BC), and suppressed rebellions started in 500 BC, leading to the Battle of Lade (494 BC).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The navy had lost its presence in the Aegean Sea, and its strength was reduced.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] 468 BC), the Persians were defeated and lost 200 ships according to the account of Thucydides.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The next significant defeat occurred in c.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] 450 BC, when they lost a war in Cyprus (near modern-day Larnaca).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The creation the organization, infrastructure, and financial basis of the Achaemenid navy is attributed to Darius I.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The coasts of Phoenicia, as well as Cyprus and Cilicia, always played a strategic role in the Achaemenid navy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Strabo and Herodotus mentioned two central bases for the navy: one in Cilicia and the other in Kyme–Phocaea (both located in modern-day Turkey).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Centers that trained crew for vessels were isolated from the central bases.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The Cilician base was heavily guarded by a large number of troops, whose payments were financed by the local tributes in that satrapy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] It is likely that Acco served as the third main base.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] According to Kaveh Farrokh, the first naval headquarters that hosted high command of the navy was located along the Shatt al-Arab, where it leads to the Persian Gulf (located in the modern-day Khuzestan Province of Iran).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] However, Cilicia was the main base and was always ready for deployment because unlike Shatt al-Arab, it was intended for power projection.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Smaller squadrons were stationed elsewhere, like those of Sidon and Halicarnassus, as well as Samos.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] An important base was a shipyard located at Tripolis, where Lebanese timber were nearby.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The Nile valley also served as a strategic base of operation, when Egypt was a satrapy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid settlements like Bahrain, Oman, Yemen and the Indian subcontinent were regular destinations for naval ships.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] It is thought likely that bases existed in Abdera and Myus, though this is uncertain.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces had an active presence in the Black Sea, the Aegean Sea, the Mediterranean Sea and the Persian Gulf among others.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] They operated patrols in river or littoral environments like Shatt al-Arab and Euphrates in Mesopotamia, Nile in Egypt and Sind in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The command hierarchy of the navy is not certain, but Greek sources indicate that high commanders were selected from the imperial aristocracy.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] There are reports of commanders of ships, and commanding officers of fleets with various non-Persians backgrounds, such as those of Carians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Commanders of Greek origin are also reported to have served in the navy, including even one Athenian.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Almost nothing is known about sailors of lower rank.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] In the wake of creating the navy, Persians hired Phoenician rowers and sailors, but later recruited from other subject peoples.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The marines standing in the forces were either Persians, Medes, or Scythians.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The servicemen were probably employed with full payment, because lengthy deployments imposed a drastic change to their communities especially if it included one or two harvests.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The first Achaemenid naval vessels, which were built at Phoenician shipyards, measured 40 meters (130 ft) in length and 6 meters (20 ft) width, and were capable of carrying 300 troops at best.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] According to Christopher Tuplin, Cypriot ships "appear a significant element in Persian fleets on various occasions".
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The Persians were the first nation to use triremes in significant numbers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The first large trireme was commissioned by Cambyses.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] By 490 BC, the backbone of the fleet was consisted of triremes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Some triremes were modified as troopers, as well as some for carrying horses and supplies or building bridges.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Persian triremes differed from those of the Greek, and used Phoenician design.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The third level of rowers in Greek vessels was accommodated by adding a outrigger, but the Persians added to the height of the compartment instead.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] They reportedly were 110 feet (34 m) to 120 feet (37 m) long and had a beam of 15 feet (4.6 m).
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The ships were most likely capable of reaching 12 knots (22 km/h) under good sailing conditions.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] They could reach full speed in 30 seconds from a dead stop.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Equipped with one mast with square sail, the triremes had rudders made up of two bladed oars, one on each side of stern, united by a crossbar.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The ram was made out of bronze, and was long and tapered to a single point.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The metal rams were designed to slice into the hulls of enemy ships after an impact.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Equipment included grappling hooks (used to catch and halt enemy ships) and two mangonels, the latter throwing stones or flammable projectiles.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] A typical Persian trireme is reported to have had 170 rowers, with the upper file carrying 62, and the middle and lower files each 54.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] In addition to the rowers, other personnel aboard triremes included 14 marines and some spare rowers and oars in case they were needed.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] In 480 BC, each trireme carried 200 men and 30 marines, according to Herodotus.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Triremes were too crowded to store their own supplies, and relied on support vessels for food and water.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] It was normal for the crew to disembark in the evening for eating and sleep.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid navy later used more advanced vessels like quinqueremes.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Other types of vessel in the fleet were triaconters, penteconters and light boats.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Smaller vessels used for river patrols could carry a maximum of 100–200 troops.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The navy operated a large number of vessels used to carry food and other supplies, which commonly had a displacement of 100 to 150 tons, at the time they invaded Egypt in 373 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Ships capable of carrying 350 to 500 tons were also used in significant numbers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] They also had horse transporters (*hippagogoi*) specifically built for this purpose, that could easily carry 30 horses.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Persian horse transport ships were good sailing ships that took advantage of the favorable winds, according to Anthony J.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Papalas, who adds they were probably designed to match the speed of a trireme.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] It is probable that horse transports were galleys with a shallow draft, that allowed horses get off in the waters and embark via a ramp.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenids are known to have used vessels for connecting the banks of rivers.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The bridges were built by joining vessels to one another and lashing them together, to erect a roadway with planks.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon reports such bridges, one made using 37 boats on Tigris, and another using seven on Maeander.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] During its early years under Cambyses, the Achaemenid navy is assumed to possess about 300 triremes, which was equal to the sum of the fleet of Egypt and its ally Polycrates of Samos.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] This number was later doubled, with 600 triremes mentioned in 494 and 490 BC.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The initial set-up of the navy (300 triremes) may have had up to 51,000 rowers and thousands of sailors and marines.
[src:sailing-ship-tactics/achaemenid-navy] The original number of vessels in the fleet was eventually quadrupled, according to Greek sources.
